Title: Trocador
Notes:
Note that Trocador only performs the service of aggregating instant exchanges (we work as a referral business only), we don't receive, process or even have access to users' funds at any point during the process. The transactions are entirely handled by the exchange provider the users choose. On these instant exchanges the user doesn't always have to create a user account, but they do leave a trail of information regarding their device and connection.

To clarify how Trocador operates:

  • The user inputs which      cryptocurrencies and amounts they wish to swap/exchange;

  • We search for the rates the listed      exchanges would offer for that trade and present that information to the      user;

  • The user selects which exchange      they want to use and inputs the receiving address they want the      provider to send the funds to after the swap;

  • The trade is generated by      the exchange provider on their server

  • We collect the information about      the generated trade with the provider and display this information to the      user;

  • The user transfers their funds to      the chosen provider's deposit address, At this stage, the      exchange provider is expected to perform AML checks on the funds,      or follow other specific compliance requirements. If the funds are deemed      safe, the exchange provider swaps them and sends it to the user's      receiving address;

  • We reiterate that the customer's      counterparty is always the chosen provider, as stated in our Terms of      Service.

  • If the user fails to deposit the      funds to the provider's deposit address before a given deadline (specific      to each provider), the transaction's status will be listed as Expired      or Waiting. These transactions were initiated, but never completed, so      no associated deposit should be expected in the User's receiving address.      Sometimes halted transactions (due to failed AML assessments on the part      of the provider) might also be listed as waiting or expired;

As the transaction is executed entirely by the exchange provider, any account registration or KYC requirements would be handled by them, according to their compliance requirements. However, as mentioned, the user does leave a trail of information, which we store for cases like this, and in accordance to the providers requests.

The information we have about the orders are (at the moment they chose the exchange provider):

  • IP from the device,

  • UserAgent,

  • AcceptLang,

  • User Browsing Session ID: used to uniquely      identify when an internet browser connects to our platform. This can be      used to more assertively tell when the same computer was used to make      multiple transactions before the browser history was erased, or a certain      time has passed. This can be ascertained when there are multiple      transactions sharing the same Browsing Session ID.
